<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="38" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1437,151,529]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,320,309,335]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Remarks.</emphasis>
The complete lack of microtrichia in the narrow subbasal section of wing cell br places this species in sg. 
<taxonomicName box="[322,469,348,373]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Lophodacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[322,469,348,373]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Lophodacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is similar to members of the 
<taxonomicName box="[865,946,348,374]" class="Insecta" family="Lauxaniidae" genus="Dacus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="triater">Triater</taxonomicName>
group (no face spot, triangular mark on scutellum, no male pecten) except in having the notopleural xanthine connected to the callus. The xanthine is medially narrowed, not in the form of a distinct wedge (as in 
<taxonomicName authority="Collart, 1935" authorityName="Collart" authorityYear="1935" box="[937,1019,425,451]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Didacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevis">Brevis</taxonomicName>
group), which suggests doubtful homology. However, no species of sg. 
<taxonomicName box="[625,772,464,489]" class="Insecta" family="Tephritidae" genus="Lophodacus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[625,772,464,489]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Lophodacus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known to have an isolated notopleural xanthine. Its unique wing pattern makes it an easy species to recognise.
</paragraph>
